P.S.—I ought perhaps to have noticed the word “ disparat& in its proper place. This term is variously used and defined by differ- ent writers. According to some, “disparates” are-—‘ things so unlike that they cannot be compared together ς’ according to others, they are—‘ different species under the same genus :’ but Cicero and Quinctilian employ the term in the sense of ‘ negative- opposite,' (disparata, ut ‘ dura’ ‘non duris! Quinct. Inst. Orat. Gernh. V. 11, 31.) It is in the last acceptation that it is com- monly used by Mr Ferme.
